SIMPLE: surcoat
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Surcoat
<hw>Sur"coat`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>surcote</ets>, OF. <ets>surcote</ets>. See <er>Sur-</er>, and
<er>Coat</er>, and cf. <er>Overcoat</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A coat
worn over the other garments; especially, the long and flowing garment
of knights, worn over the armor, and frequently emblazoned with the arms
of the wearer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A long <qex>surcoat</qex> of pers upon he had..</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At night, or in the rain,⟦br⟧
He dons a <qex>surcoat</qex> which he doffs at morn.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A name given to the outer garment of either sex at
different epochs of the Middle Ages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surcrew</ent>⟦br⟧
